<paragraph id="B95CFD309C5E2A14EF915F3BFD265C8D" blockId="38.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EF915F3BFED15C3D" bold="true" box="[199,343,260,285]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Bio-ecology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="7EE386B39C5E2A14EE365F3AFE4D5C3D" baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[352,459,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EE365F3AFE4D5C3D" box="[352,459,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">M. lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a poorly known species exclusively reported for coastal sites characterized by the presence of well preserved sand dunes. The larvae were collected in proximity of isolated junipers on open dunes, buried at the base of junipers and among their roots. In these conditions, the substratum is always composed by clean sand, without conspicuous quantities of organic debris except juniper needles. They are apparently absent from back dunes with a more thick vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F1F9AEBB9C5E2A14EF915F88FEA75CD5" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B95CFD309C5E2A14EF915F88FEA75CD5" blockId="38.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EF915F88FEE65CF0" bold="true" box="[199,352,439,464]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Distribution.</emphasis>
This very rare species is known for few coastal localities in 
<collectingRegion id="7B2733D29C5E2A14EB415F88FBF15CF0" box="[1047,1143,439,464]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
, Tyrrhenian 
<collectingCountry id="C1F4BDA09C5E2A14EA515F88FABD5CF0" box="[1287,1339,439,464]" name="Italy" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Italy</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="C1F4BDA09C5E2A14EA1E5F88FA1A5CF0" box="[1352,1436,439,464]" name="Algeria" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Algeria</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="C1F4BDA09C5E2A14EF905FE3FE9B5CD5" box="[198,285,476,501]" name="Tunisia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F1F9AEBB9C5E2A14EF915FC0FB6E5F1D" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B95CFD309C5E2A14EF915FC0FB6E5F1D" blockId="38.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EF915FC0FEBD5F38" bold="true" box="[199,315,511,536]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</emphasis>
The larva of 
<taxonomicName id="7EE386B39C5E2A14EE825C3EFDB85F38" baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[468,574,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EE825C3EFDB85F38" box="[468,574,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">M. lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by an unmistakable habitus reminding 
<emphasis id="8B9721229C5E2A14EBE55C3FFAC35F37" box="[1203,1349,512,535]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName id="7EE386B39C5E2A14EBE55C3FFAC75F37" baseAuthorityName="Schneider" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1203,1345,512,535]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Gymnocnemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">G. variegata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
despite the two species are easily set apart by the shape of the mandibles and the different hue of the body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
